This RMarkdown file contains R code you can use to complete the exercise on reproducibility. To see the output simply click on Knit to HTML above. This might prompt you to install and load some required packages, specifically knitr.

Packages:

We will use packages from tidyverse, a collection of R packages that share common philosophies and are designed to work together.

If you have not yet done so, install tidyverse via install.packages(tidyverse).

Now we need to explicitly load the tidyverse packages:

  library("tidyverse")

Part 1: Analyze + document

1. Load the data:

Note that read_csv uses stringsAsFactors = FALSE by default.

  gap_5060 <- read_csv("../0_data/gapminder-5060.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(

2. Visualize life expectancy over time for Canada in the 1950s and 1960s using a line plot.

# Filter the data for Canada only
  gap_5060_CA <- 
    gap_5060 %>%
    filter(country == "Canada")
# Visualize
  ggplot(data = gap_5060_CA, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp)) +
    geom_line()

Something is clearly wrong with this plot! In 1957 people lived excpetionlly long lives.

3. Make appropriate corrections.

Life expectancy shouldnt exceed even the most extreme age observed for humans. The following is one way to test for this:

Turns out theres a data error in the data file: life expectancy for Canada in the year 1957 is coded as 999999, it should actually be 69.96. We now make this correction:

  gap_5060 <- 
    gap_5060 %>%
    mutate(lifeExp = replace(lifeExp, (country == "Canada" & year == 1957), 69.96))

Hey - we changed the problematic value AND documented it in one go - awesome!

4. Visualize life expectancy over time for Canada again, with the corrected data.

Exact same code as before, but note that the contents of gap_5060 are different as it has been updated in the previous task.

  gap_5060_CA <- 
    gap_5060 %>%
    filter(country == "Canada")

  ggplot(data = gap_5060_CA, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp)) +
    geom_line()

4 - Stretch goal. Add lines for Mexico and United States.

  • %in% for logical operator testing if a countrys name is in the list provided
  • Same visualization code as before, only difference is the input dataset
  gap_5060_multiple <- 
    gap_5060 %>%
    filter(country %in% c("Canada", "Mexico", "United States"))

  ggplot(data = gap_5060_multiple, aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, color = country)) +
    geom_line()
